descript.abstract: The Streets table includes all navigable links (in the HERE Map Content’s standard road network - this excludes links classified as Supplemental Geometry), with their attribution relevant for route calculation and route guidance. Additionally the preferred name of the Link is included to enable Street Names to be included in the guidance (e.g. ‘Turn right at Montrose Boulevard’).
descript.purpose: Road network navigation and routing, geocoding, location-based services, and base mapping applications.

idinfo.datacred: HERE incorporates and enhances data from a number of local governments, utility companies, other public agencies, and commercial mapping agencies in building its final products.

attracc.attraccr: HERE advanced map-building capabilities, local field staff and a fleet of LIDAR equipped TRUE vehicles capture the world down to centimeter level precision to build a virtual 3D model of the real world. In addition, internal test applications are regularly run on attributes to assist in verification and correction.

dataqual.logic: HERE publishes Technical Notification Memorandums (TNM) for customers on a quarterly and weekly basis via HERE TNM Web Portal. These TNMs include information pertaining to product updates, format changes, new attributes, detailed attribute specifications and representations, and new country coverage announcements. If HERE plans to add, remove, or change an attribute or product Layer, an announcement is made to customers a minimum of 6 months in advance. This allows customers to prepare and make necessary modifications to their applications before a new attribute is released in the product.
dataqual.complete: HERE includes 4 levels of street map coverage: Prime, Complete, Network, and City-to-City. Prime is HERE's highest level of coverage. This coverage level has the most detail and enables door-to-door routing functionality. Complete is a level of coverage, which is source dependent. It is the coverage level used for links that are not field verified and are flagged with the In-Process Data attribute = Y. Network coverage includes the main highway network and all the necessary attributes required to allow routing from city to city. Network links are coded with Detailed City Inclusion attribute = N and In-Process Data attribute = N. For Network links, the Full Geometry flag may be set to either yes or no depending on the presence or lack of surrounding In-Process Data Coverage. The City-to-City specification enables HERE to maintain minimum coverage in areas prior to completing Prime, Network, or In- Process areas. Examples include: major roads only in a country where there is no existing coverage, major roads to a city in a country where there is currently no other existing coverage, or major roads between existing DC/Prime, IT/Network, or In-Process areas. In many countries, HERE has used a commercial source to add local roads to the Inter-Town network. The inclusion of this geometry allows improved map display and guidance. This coverage level is called Full Coverage in the U.S. and Road Network Coverage in Europe. The Connector Specification enables HERE to maintain minimum coverage in areas prior to completing (full) Prime, Network/Inter Town (IT), or In-Process areas. For defining a hierarchical network used to determine a logical and efficient route for a traveler, each map street segment is tagged with a 5 level Functional Class (FC) attribute explained as follows. FC 1: Very long distance routes between major cities - The "highest level" network comprises the FC 1 arterials, which are primarily controlled access highways designed for very-long-distance travel linking major metropolitan areas and cities, FC 2: Primary routes between major and smaller cities and through metro areas, FC 3: Major routes between minor cities or towns, and through city districts, FC 4: Routes connecting minor towns or villages and collecting the local traffic in the city districts, and FC 5: Roads that are not efficient through routes - The "lowest level" and final category is FC 5, which comprises roads not considered to be arterials or transportation corridors.

horizpa.horizpar: The positional accuracy of a given street segment depends on the value of the Enhanced Geometry (ENH_GEOM) attribute. Links with Enhanced Geometry = Y conform to accuracy requirements of +/-5 metres for absolute position and +/- 1 metre for relative position. NOTE: With some linear SDC datasets, there can be 5 different representations of linear street geometry, including one base layer plus 4 increasingly generalized layers, to support rapid display at different zoom levels. The process of generalization removes points, and therefore geometric detail, from the dataset in order to reduce dataset size and improve display times. The suffix number at the end of the base layer name indicates how much generalization has been applied - the higher the number, the more generalization. For example, streets3 is more generalized than streets2. The horizontal positional accuracy described here does NOT apply to these generalized layers, but only to the non-generalized base layer, which will not have a suffix number as part of its name, e.g., streets. The minimum length of any street segment, independent of generalization, is 2 meters/7 feet.

procstep.procdesc: HERE File Geodatabase Plus is assembled from the following data sources: HERE North America FGDB, HERE Traffic Patterns, HERE Postal Code Boundaries, and HERE enhanced network routing and geocoding data entities and locators.

Using proprietary tools and processes, HERE collects road geometry and approximately 400 road attributes. Proprietary software is used to add navigable information, addresses, and points of interest. TRUE vehicles and photos capture overhead signage to ensure that the data accurately reflects the real world.

HERE relies on local source data and input from map users to generate constant daily map updates, such as real time traffic, turn by turn directions, public transportation routes and information about local business and attractions.
HERE allows end users to update map content through the HERE Map Creator program, which provides online cartographic and data editing capabilities (https://mapcreator.here.com).

attr.attrdef: Object ID - ESRI unique ID.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all OBJECTID values

attr.attrdef: Shape - ESRI geometry object.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all Shape values

attr.attrdef: FromNodeID - Unique identifier for the From Reference Node of the Link.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all FromNodeID values

attr.attrdef: To Node ID - Unique identifier for the To Reference Node of the Link.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all ToNodeID values

attr.attrdef: Street Name Lng - Street Name Language Code is the Language Code that is applicable to the Street Name. The Language Code in the Streets layer represents the ISO639-1 language code (e.g., ‘en’) which is a two character language code. Only cultural-neutral langauge codes are published. HERE does not publish culturally-specific language codes like, for example, “en-US’ or ‘nl-NL’.
Street Name - The Street Name attribute is the full spelling of the street name including the Street Name Prefix, Street Name Suffix and Street Type.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetName values

attr.attrdef: Street Name Prefix - Street Name Prefix is a directional identifier that precedes the Street Name of a road. The Street Name Prefix is included in the full name for roads. The full name should be used for route guidance and destination selection instead of individual components Street Name Prefix, Street Type, Street Name, and Street Name Suffix. If the full name is used for display or destination input list the Street Name Prefix should not be displayed after the name or Street Type, this may allow the Street Name Prefix to be confused with the Street Name Suffix.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetNamePrefix values

attr.attrdef: Street Type Before - Street Type Before provides the Street Type of the Street Name, but it is only published when the Street Type appears before the Street Name. Street Type Before can be used to determine the placement of the Street Type for usage in destination selection, map display and route guidance.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetTypeBefore values

attr.attrdef: Street Name Base - Street Name Base is the Base Name of the Street Name.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetNameBase values

attr.attrdef: Street Type After - Street Type After is the Street Type of the Street Name. It is only published when the Street Type appears after the Base Name. See 5.58.8 Street Type Before (Streets).

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetTypeAfter values

attr.attrdef: Street Name Suffix - A Street Name Suffix is a directional identifier that follows, but is not included in, the Street Name of a road. The Street Name Suffix is included in the full name for roads. The full name should be used for route guidance and destination selection instead of individual components Street Name Prefix, Street Type, Street Name, and Street Name Suffix. If the full name is used for display or destination input list the Street Name Prefix should not be displayed after the name or Street Type, this may allow the Street Name Prefix to be confused with the Street Name Suffix.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all StreetNameSuffix values

attr.attrdef: Direction On Sign - The official directional identifiers assigned to highways. Direction on Sign should be used in conjunction with Feature Name, Name on Road Sign, and Name Route Type. For route guidance, US-101 South should be used and not just US-101 when appropriate.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all DirOnSign values

attr.attrdef: Meters - Meters indicates the length of the Link in meters.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all Meters values

attr.attrdef: SpeedCat - Speed Category classifies the general speed trend of a road based on posted or legal speed and is provided to enhance route calculation and the timing of route guidance. Speed Category values represent the combination of several factors besides legal speed limit (e.g., physical restrictions or access characteristics). Therefore Speed Category values can differ from the From/To Reference Speed Limit values, which represent the legal speed limit only. Speed Category may be used to estimate link traversal times, to prioritise link selection during route calculation, and to calculate timing of the route guidance.

Functional Class - Functional Class defines the arterial classification (hierarchical network) used to determine a logical and efficient route for a traveller. Functional Class can be used to determine sets of links that form connected graphs.

Direction Of Travel - Direction of Travel identifies legal travel directions for a navigable link. Direction of Travel enables correct route calculation, route guidance, and map display. For example, display of one-way icon.

ContrAcc - Controlled Access identifies roads with limited entrances and exits that allow uninterrupted high speed traffic flow. These roads constitute the interstate/freeway network in the U.S. and the motorway network in Europe. The Controlled Access attribute can be used for map display, avoidance of freeway/motorway, and route guidance timing.

FerryType - An attribute that defines whether a link is or is not a ferry link. If the link is a ferry link, Ferry Type will describe if it is a boat ferry link, or a rail ferry link. It is a combination of the Boat Ferry and Rail Ferry attributes. See Table 5-97 below for Boat Ferry and Rail Ferry combinations that define the Ferry Type.

Ramp - Ramps are connectors that provide access between roads that do not cross at grade. This attribute allows explication of manoeuvres involving ramps (e.g. “Take the ramp”). This attribute can also be used for display at different zoom levels or different colors and for route guidance when determining if sign text should be used.

Roundabout - A roundabout is a contiguous loop with consistent one-way traffic throughout the circle that controls the traffic flow from converging roads. This attribute allows explication of manoeuvres involving roundabouts (i.e. “Take the third exit from roundabout”).

Paved - Describes roads that are made of materials which create a solid surface. Paved is primarily used for cartographic representation (map display). This attribute could also affect routing algorithms by assigning higher penalties to unpaved roads.

Public Access - The Public Access attribute indicates whether or not the Link allows public access. Route Calculation: The Public Access attribute indicates if the road element can be used in route calculation to avoid specific navigable links. Route Guidance: The Public Access attribute can be used in route guidance for additional guidance instructions. Map Display: The Public Access attribute can be used in map display to differentiate navigable links.

Tollway - This attribute identifies a link for which a fee must be paid to use the road. Tollway identifies roads that require payments for traversal. This attribute’s intended uses are display and map publishing purposes. This attribute used in conjunction with the Toll Structure condition may be used for toll avoidance routing.
Time Zone - Time Zone indicates the GMT time zone in which the Link is located. Time Zone can be used to identify the time zone applicable to an administrative area.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all Time_Zone values

attr.attrdef: DST Exist - Indicates if the Link is located in an administrative area where Daylight Saving Time (DST) is observed.
Time Zone ID - Not published by HERE.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all TimeZoneID values

attr.attrdef: Restrict Cars - Indicates if Passenger Cars are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Buses - Indicates if Buses are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Taxis - Indicates if Taxis are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Pedestrians - Indicates if Pedestrians are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Deliveries - Indicates if Delivery vehicles are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Trucks - Indicates if Trucks are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Carpools - Indicates if the Link is restricted to Carpool use only.
Restrict Emergencies - Indicates if Emergency Vehicles are restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Through Traffic - Indicates if Through Traffic is restricted from using the Link.
Restrict Motorcycles - Indicates if Motorcycles are restricted from using the Link.
Link ID - Unique identifier for the Link to which the Street Address relates. Link ID is used to identify each link in the database.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all Link_ID values

attr.attrdef: ISO Country Code - A three-letter country code as defined by the International Organization for Standardization. The ISO Country Code indicates in which country the feature is located. Different layers describe different features. ISO Country Code attribution is applied to Navigable Links, Administrative Hierarchies, and POIs in various layers.

CarpoolRoad - The Carpool Road attribute identifies a Link where, at specific times, all lanes serve as carpool lanes. Carpool Road can be used to avoid Carpool links in the routing, and for explicit instructions (guidance) in relation to Carpool links.
ExpressLane - The Express Lane attribute identifies Links that serve as express lanes. Express Lane can be used to optimize the current route by taking the express lane.
Shape Length - ESRI automatically caluclated shape length, not to be used for actual linear calculations, e.g., square miles.

attrdomv.udom: The set of all Shape_Length values
